    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="255"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d255">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751.13/12–3054</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Prime
                        Minister <persName corresp="#p_MENDESFP1" type="to">Mendès-France</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d255fn1">This message was transmitted to Paris at 3 p.m. in
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss> telegram 2364, Dec. 30, with
                        instructions for the Ambassador to communicate it to <persName
                            corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendès-France</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">limited official use</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-12-30">December 30,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Prime Minister</hi>: I extend to you my warmest
                    congratulations on the successful struggle you have led. I think I can
                    appreciate how arduous the task has been. I followed every phase with intense
                    interest and if we here said little it was because we felt that silence was the
                    best contribution we could make. I am sure, however, that you <pb facs="0471"
                        n="1539" xml:id="pg_1539"/> and others in France must have realized the
                    intensity of our concern. With best wishes to you and your wife for the New
                    Year, I am</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d255fn2">In telegram 2767 from Paris, Dec. 31, <persName
                                corresp="#p_DILLONCD1">Dillon</persName> reported that he had
                            received a telephone call from <persName corresp="#p_MENDESFP1"
                                >Mendès-France</persName> that morning thanking him for the letters
                            from President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1">Eisenhower</persName>
                            and Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName>.
                                <persName corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendès-France</persName> then said
                            that the restraint exercised by the United States during the past week
                            had been of the utmost help and he was appreciative of the U.S.
                            Government’s silence. (751.13/12–3154)</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
